column51: I have been a teacher for 32 years and have always ordered from Scholastic. The last two months have been very confusing with the online ordering. Last month I called to ask why my Book of the week order in my account had disappeared when I went in to submit my order. The person on the phone did not know why. I was disappointed but sent the order. This month I ordered a week ago and then this week a new online order came in from a parent so I opened it  up and saw the old Book of the Month order in the account. It was under Teachers order. This did not combine or get submitted with my order last week. I have never been so confused with ordering from the Scholastic website. There is a teacher order and student orders, and they do not combine.... not sure what this is about. I also wasn't sure if my order from last week was actually submitted because that still showed up in my cart I also was not able to access the dollar books last week and then it was an option today. DO BETTER!

Families often will not respond to monthly book orders, even when I send home the traditional flyers or options for online ordering.     I used to order class sets of books regularly (almost monthly) to support ELA instruction, and to allow students to build their personal libraries to bring home with them. The limited choices & increased prices has not allowed me to do this because of the increase in numbers of students that I often work with (typically a full classroom of  30 students or close to it)

column51: I just wanted to say that I will be retiring after teaching and using Scholastic for 32 years.  I spent  the first 18 years of my career teaching 2nd grade and 1 teaching 4th before moving to 6th grade.  In each of these positions, I have sent home your flyers and had many, many students purchase.  I remember the years when almost my entire class purchased Louis Sachar’s Sideways Stories from Wayside School because I read it to them and they loved it so much.  Thank you for all the freebies, for stocking my classroom library, and for your great customer service.  I will continue to recommend you to everyone and you are yet another part of teaching that I will miss in my retirement.

column38: Other, Billing/invoicing issue
column51: Your links for the user to view their profile, billing, payment options, etc. are redundant - and none of them are helpful. I expect to see a history of orders placed, payments made, and all invoices sent to me. Plus there should be notes for all the invoicing errors, or every time Scholastic lost track of a payment. There should be an option to see an invoice and make a payment based on the invoice, or even an option to pay all invoice balances at once. I need to see information on the site that mirrors the most recently emailed statement (which is telling me I have a negative amount due, and, for reference, owing a negative amount is equivalent to the customer being due a refund). The current website UX can be so much better. Please reach out for additional consulting and feedback. I love Scholastic books, but the website and billing process are decreasing your revenue.

column51: Tried to order a book (I guess it's new and in high demand) and when I checked with my son's teacher about the delivery date, she said she received notification that it was cancelled and the parent was notified. I had no indication on my end until over two weeks later when I finally received the email notification that the order would not be going through. (Bummer when I was hoping for it to be an Easter gift.) Now when I logged in to see the order information again it has disappeared entirely. I think there should still be a record that I attempted to make an order and it was cancelled rather than delete it and hide it from view. Do better at communicating with customers and communicating inventory status in your system so we don't order products that are not actually available or will take months to receive. (That has happened in the past to me as well.)

column51: My satisfaction with this site would be a 5 if you were able to fix a glitch in the system. It's one that many teachers talk about and we've expressed this concern to you, yet you don't respond with an answer and the problem continues. The problem is that when we have 2 or more students in our classroom with the same first name, it causes problems when the books arrive and there's no record of which student's parent ordered them. The classroom teacher has to then track down and have an uncomfortable conversation with at least one of the parents who didn't order. I am once again taking the time to address this problem and am really wishing one of these years somebody will listen and do something. Thank you!
